## Architecture rules

- Dependency flow: `arvo → arvo-bits → arvo-bitmask`; `arvo →
  arvo-tensor` (L2 peer of bitmask); L2 algorithm crates depend on
  `arvo`, `arvo-bitmask`, and `arvo-tensor` (not `arvo-bits`
  directly); `arvo-spectral` depends on `arvo`, `arvo-sparse`,
  and `arvo-tensor`.
- `arvo-bits` hosts bit-level contracts plus a small allowlist of
  opaque-bit concrete containers (`Bits<const N: u8>`). Arithmetic
  fielded types (UFixed, IFixed) belong in L0 `arvo`; mask concretes
  (Mask64, Mask256, BitMatrix) belong in `arvo-bitmask`. New
  opaque-bit types extend the allowlist via a design round; the
  `arvo-bits-traits-only` lint is the backstop.
- Algorithm crates are generic over numeric trait bounds. They do not
  import `UFixed` or `IFixed` directly.
- Every numeric type that has a precision/throughput tradeoff carries
  `S: Strategy`. Default `Warm`.
- Monomorphisation is the dispatch. No `dyn`, no `TypeId`, no
  `std::any`.
- `#![no_std]` in every crate. No `alloc`, no `Vec`, no `String`,
  no `Box`.
- Sizes are const. No runtime grow: no `.push(`, `.resize(`,
  `.extend(`.
- No platform dep: no `std::thread`, `std::time`, `std::fs`,
  `std::net`.

## Consumers

arvo is a library; real code lives downstream. Known consumers:

- **hilavitkutin** — pipeline execution engine. Uses `arvo-graph`
  for plan-stage DAG analysis, `arvo-bitmask` for `AccessMask`,
  `arvo-sparse` for RCM reordering, `arvo-spectral` for trunk
  formation, `arvo-comb` for fiber grouping.
- **clause** — language toolchain. Uses `arvo-graph` for pass DAGs
  and `arvo-bitmask` for artifact read/write sets.

Consumer names appear here only because they drive the choice of
which L2/L3 algorithms exist. arvo's API is not shaped by any one
consumer; the substrate stays usable by anyone.

## Commit style

Format: `type: lowercase imperative message`. See
`skills/commit-style/SKILL.md`.

Byline policy is configured in `mock/agent/config.toml`
`[attribution]`. The built-in `check-byline.sh` hook enforces it at
commit time.

## Where things live

- `docs/DESIGN.md` — generated, canonical architecture.
- `docs/STRUCTURE.md` + graph — generated, crate and item index.
- `mock/DESIGN.md.tmpl`, `mock/PRINCIPLES.md.tmpl`,
  `mock/WORKFLOW.md.tmpl` — authored sources.
- `mock/crates/*/DESIGN.md.tmpl` — per-crate deep dives.
- `mock/design_rounds/` — design round state machine. Do not rename
  files by hand; use `cargo mock lock` / `unlock` / `deprecate` /
  `close`.
- `mock/agent/` — these instructions. Edit templates here, not the
  generated files under `.claude/` or `.github/`.

## What not to do

- Do not add `alloc`, `std`, `Vec`, `String`, `Box`, `dyn`, or
  `TypeId` to any `arvo*` crate.
- Do not put arithmetic fielded structs in `arvo-bits`. Opaque-bit
  concretes on the allowlist (today: `Bits`) are permitted;
  arithmetic types live in L0 `arvo`, masks in `arvo-bitmask`.
- Do not import `UFixed` / `IFixed` directly in `arvo-graph`,
  `arvo-sparse`, `arvo-comb`, or `arvo-spectral`. Use trait bounds.
- Do not add platform calls (`std::thread`, `std::time`, `std::fs`,
  `std::net`) anywhere.
- Do not grow collections at runtime. All sizes are const.
- Do not edit files under `.claude/`, `.github/copilot-instructions.md`,
  `.github/instructions/`, `.github/skills/`, or `.github/hooks/`.
  They regenerate from `mock/agent/` on every `cargo mock`.
- Do not hand-rename `design_rounds/*.md` suffixes. Use the
  subcommands.
